    {
      "beat_id": "B02",
      "act": "COLD OPEN",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "This is the hydrogen molecular ion, H two plus, in the fixed-nuclei picture. Same nuclei. Same electron. But the spatial shape of its wavefunction changes the total energy.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "drawon"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B02.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.82,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B02.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T19:04:54"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B03",
      "act": "THE QUESTION",
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "So what does the plus combination do that the minus combination does not? And why does only one total-energy curve develop a minimum?",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "drawon"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B03.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 7.96,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B03.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T19:04:54"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B04",
      "act": "THE PROBLEM",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "A tiny orbiting-particle cartoon misses the mechanism. The electron is described by a wavefunction, and wavefunctions carry phase. Overlapping amplitudes can reinforce or cancel.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "drawon"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B04.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 11.26,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B04.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T19:04:54"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B05",
      "act": "THE MODEL",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "Start with one one-s orbital centered on each proton. The simplest molecular trial states are a normalized sum and a normalized difference. We will keep the algebra offscreen and watch the shapes.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "drawon"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B05.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 11.43,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B05.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T19:04:54"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B06",
      "act": "THE MECHANISM",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "In the sum, the amplitudes have the same sign between the nuclei. They reinforce. Squaring the result produces extra probability density in the internuclear region.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "drawon"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B06.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.69,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B06.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T19:04:54"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B07",
      "act": "THE MECHANISM",
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "That redistribution can lower the electronic energy: the electron samples attraction to both nuclei. But call it a tendency, not magic glue. Kinetic energy and proton-proton repulsion still count.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "drawon"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B07.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 12.44,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B07.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T19:04:54"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B08",
      "act": "THE MECHANISM",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "In the difference, opposite signs cancel at the midplane. The wavefunction is zero there, so the probability density has a nodal plane between the protons.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "drawon"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B08.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.09,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B08.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T19:04:54"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B09",
      "act": "THE MECHANISM",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "The node removes density from the region that helps stabilize the two centers. In this one-electron model, the antibonding total-energy curve stays above the separated-atom limit and has no binding minimum.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "drawon"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B09.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 12.31,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B09.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T19:04:54"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B10",
      "act": "THE ENERGY TEST",
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "A bond exists only if the full energy versus separation bends down and then rises again, creating a minimum. Electron-nuclear attraction wins at intermediate range; nuclear repulsion wins when the protons get too close.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "drawon"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B10.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 13.14,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B10.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T19:04:54"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B11",
      "act": "THE EXAMPLE",
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "For H two plus, the bonding state has an equilibrium separation near one point three angstroms and binds by roughly one point eight electron-volts in the standard calculation. The antibonding state does not bind.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "drawon"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B11.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 12.82,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B11.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T19:04:54"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B12",
      "act": "RECAP",
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "The useful lesson is narrower than a slogan about every bond. Constructive overlap builds internuclear density and can stabilize a molecular orbital. Destructive overlap creates a node and raises the energy.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "drawon"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B12.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 12.54,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B12.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T19:04:54"
      }
    },
